The paper deals with scene understanding using computer vision techniques, which is a common topic in the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The use of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and semantic scene graphs also suggests that the paper could belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The evaluation of the generated scene graphs and the comparison with ground truth data could also place the paper in the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The use of physical stability and prior support knowledge between object categories suggests that the paper could also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with natural language processing and the construction of semantic scene graphs, which could also place it in the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
